---
alwaysApply: true
---

You are developing features for an enterprise-grade Fuar CRM System.

All new features must follow this mandatory development protocol.
Features are tracked in docs/phase-1-features.md with sequential numbering.
Never skip steps. Never jump directly to implementation.

This protocol integrates the full workflow: git branching, development, testing, and completion.

==============================
STEP 0 — CREATE FEATURE BRANCH
==============================

Before writing any code:

- Identify the feature number from docs/phase-1-features.md.
- Ensure you are on main branch and it is up to date.
- Create a feature branch:
  git checkout main
  git checkout -b feature/F{n}-short-description

Example:
  git checkout -b feature/F4-prisma-schema

Never start coding on main. All code changes happen on feature branches.

==============================
STEP 1 — ANALYZE BEFORE CODING
==============================

Before generating code:

- Read the full feature description and all sub-items from phase-1-features.md.
- Determine which apps are affected (api, web, shared, or combination).
- Check if previous features this one depends on are completed.
- If dependencies are not met, stop and notify the developer.
- Check if database schema changes are needed.
- Check if shared types or schemas need updating in @crm/shared.
- Review related existing modules — avoid duplicating logic (see context-and-reuse.mdc).
- Identify which files will be created or modified.

Mandatory — list before writing any code:
- Existing files to use as reference or template (e.g. apps/api/src/modules/fair/ for a new module).
- For each new unit (service, controller, component, schema, util): "Does something similar already exist? Where?"
  If yes → reuse or extend; do not add a second copy.
  If no → add in the correct place (shared vs app-specific) and follow existing patterns.

List your analysis (including the reference files and reuse check) before writing any code.

==============================
STEP 2 — SHARED PACKAGE FIRST
==============================

If the feature requires new types, schemas, or utilities:

- Define TypeScript interfaces in packages/shared/src/types/.
- Define Zod validation schemas in packages/shared/src/schemas/.
- Add constants or enums in packages/shared/src/constants/.
- Add utility functions in packages/shared/src/utils/.

Shared package changes must come before backend or frontend implementation.
Both apps will import from @crm/shared — never define locally.

>>> COMMIT: feat(shared): add types/schemas for feature F{n}

==============================
STEP 3 — DATABASE SCHEMA (IF NEEDED)
==============================

If the feature requires data persistence:

- Update Prisma schema at apps/api/prisma/schema.prisma.
- Define proper relations (@relation) with referential actions (onDelete, onUpdate).
- Add constraints: @unique, @default, optional (?), required.
- Use proper field types matching the shared TypeScript types.
- Run prisma migrate dev with a descriptive migration name.
- Run prisma generate to update the Prisma client types.

No feature should bypass data modeling.

>>> COMMIT: feat(prisma): add {model} schema
>>> COMMIT: chore(prisma): run migration {migration-name}

==============================
STEP 4 — BACKEND: VALIDATION LAYER
==============================

- Import Zod schemas from @crm/shared in the module's DTO files.
- Create DTOs that use z.infer<typeof schema> for type safety.
- Apply Zod validation pipe at controller level (@UsePipes).
- Validate request body, params, and query strings as needed.
- Reject invalid inputs early with descriptive error messages.

Validation is mandatory for every endpoint that accepts user input.

==============================
STEP 5 — BACKEND: SERVICE LAYER
==============================

- Implement all business logic in the service class.
- Inject PrismaService for database operations.
- Inject other services if cross-module logic is needed.
- Keep the service focused — one service per module.
- Handle all business rules: access control checks, data transformation, cascade operations.
- Throw typed NestJS exceptions (NotFoundException, ForbiddenException, etc.).
- Never handle HTTP concerns in services.

>>> COMMIT: feat(api): implement {Module}Service

==============================
STEP 6 — BACKEND: CONTROLLER LAYER
==============================

- Handle HTTP request and response only.
- Apply appropriate decorators: @Get, @Post, @Patch, @Delete.
- Apply guards: @UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard), @UseGuards(RolesGuard).
- Apply roles: @Roles('admin') where needed.
- Call service methods — no business logic in controllers.
- Return standardized response format: { success, message, data }.
- Use proper HTTP status codes via @HttpCode decorator.

>>> COMMIT: feat(api): add {Module}Controller with endpoints

==============================
STEP 7 — BACKEND: REGISTER MODULE
==============================

- Register the new module in apps/api/src/app.module.ts.
- Export services that other modules may need.
- Ensure proper dependency injection setup.
- Verify the module loads without errors.

>>> COMMIT: feat(api): register {Module} in AppModule

==============================
STEP 8 — FRONTEND: DATA LAYER
==============================

If the feature has a frontend component:

- Create TanStack Query hooks in apps/web/src/hooks/:
  Query hooks for data fetching (useQuery).
  Mutation hooks for create/update/delete (useMutation).
- Define query keys in apps/web/src/lib/query-keys.ts.
- Configure cache invalidation: mutations should invalidate related queries.
- Import types from @crm/shared for type-safe API responses.

>>> COMMIT: feat(web): add data hooks for {feature}

==============================
STEP 9 — FRONTEND: UI COMPONENTS
==============================

- Create components in the appropriate directory:
  Shared/reusable: apps/web/src/components/ui/
  Feature-specific: apps/web/src/components/fair/, apps/web/src/components/customer/
- Follow the design system defined in docs/phase-1-features.md (Feature 14):
  Use TailwindCSS tokens — never hardcode colors.
  Use Playfair Display for headings, DM Sans for body text.
  Follow the spacing hierarchy.
- Use React Hook Form + Zod schemas from @crm/shared for forms.
- Use shadcn/ui base components — extend, don't rewrite.
- Keep components under 150 lines — extract sub-components.

>>> COMMIT: feat(web): implement {Component} component

==============================
STEP 10 — FRONTEND: PAGE INTEGRATION
==============================

- Wire components into the page in apps/web/src/app/.
- Connect TanStack Query hooks for data.
- Connect Zustand stores for UI state (modals, selectedFair).
- Handle loading, error, and empty states.
- Verify the full user flow works end-to-end.

>>> COMMIT: feat(web): integrate {feature} page

==============================
STEP 11 — WRITE TESTS
==============================

- Write unit tests for new service methods (backend).
- Write unit tests for new Zod schemas (shared).
- Write unit tests for new utility functions (shared).
- Write component tests for complex UI components (frontend).
- Test edge cases: empty fields, long text, special characters, no data.
- Test authorization: protected endpoints reject unauthorized access.
- Test validation: invalid inputs are rejected with proper messages.

All tests must pass before proceeding.

>>> COMMIT: test(api): add tests for {Module}Service
>>> COMMIT: test(shared): add tests for {schema/util}
>>> COMMIT: test(web): add tests for {Component}

==============================
STEP 12 — VERIFICATION
==============================

Before merging to main, verify:

- All CRUD operations work correctly (if applicable).
- No TypeScript errors across all apps (tsc --noEmit).
- No lint errors (npm run lint).
- All tests pass (npm test).
- No console errors in browser (if UI feature).
- Responsive layout works (if UI feature).

DO NOT merge to main if any of these checks fail.

==============================
STEP 13 — MERGE TO MAIN & COMPLETE
==============================

After all verifications pass:

1. Merge feature branch to main:
   git checkout main
   git merge feature/F{n}-short-description

2. Delete the feature branch:
   git branch -d feature/F{n}-short-description

3. Update feature status (commit directly on main):
   Update docs/phase-1-features.md: [ ] → [x]
   git commit -m "docs: mark feature F{n} as complete"

4. Proceed to the next sequential feature number.

==============================
IMPORTANT RULES
==============================

- Never create quick temporary solutions — do it right the first time.
- Never break modular architecture for convenience.
- Never introduce tight coupling between modules.
- Never skip the shared package step — duplication is not acceptable.
- Never merge to main without passing all checks in Step 12.
- Never commit directly to main (except doc updates in Step 13).
- Keep future extensibility in mind (Phase 2 mobile app will consume the same API).
- If uncertain about implementation approach, ask before coding.
- Reference docs/tech-stack.md for allowed technologies at all times.
- Not all features require all steps — skip steps that don't apply
  (e.g., pure frontend features skip Steps 3-7).
